personality_type.name: Agreeableness
personality_type.description: Influencing people (Agreeableness) concerns the way someone balances their emotional understanding of other people, and their respect for differing viewpoints, with the style in which they try to influence or negotiate with them.

details.title: first_person_description
details.body: You describe yourself as someone who has a mature and streetwise view of other people and their views. Your first instinct is likely to be to trust other people, but you do know that others can let you down. Thus, while you are a loyal friend and colleague, you do not take everything on trust. Your results indicate that you tend to have an attitude towards others that is built on openness and a view that people are imperfect and sometimes need help. Therefore, when you deal with other people, you will search for a mutually acceptable outcome, because you know that you need to work together. In this way, you are probably able to be direct, but are also able to temper your approach with sensitivity for what will keep relationships healthy and intact.

details.title: first_person_description
details.body: You come across as someone who is comfortable in social situations, but who also knows when to withdraw for periods of quiet reflection. Your results indicate that you are likely to be able to adapt your interpersonal approach, depending on the situation, with the result that you are able to connect easily with different types of people. However, you are just as likely to be found lost in thought as you are lost in conversation! When it comes to the energy you put into life, you're content being where the action is, but are also able to vary your level of enthusiasm so that you don't come across as being too attention-grabbing. Generally, you're the kind of person who has a good idea of the amount of excitement you would like - however, you can find too much 'down-time' de-motivating.

personality_type.name: Conscientiousness
personality_type.description: Delivering Results (Conscientiousness) concerns work style and how someone directs their efforts and attention toward completing tasks. The level of discipline, dedication, perseverance, organization and reliability are hallmark factors of this dimension.

details.title: first_person_description
details.body: You seem to be the sort of person who prefers to weigh the extent to which tasks need to be structured, organized and planned. You are likely to be aware of the fact that there are things that need to be approached in a highly methodical manner, and equally, that there are occasions when action is more important than following a pre-planned approach.  Based on your results, you seem to be the type of person who can measure out the energy you invest in tasks, ramping up more when you have to do things you would normally avoid. This view of how work should be done is reinforced by the fact that you are likely to commit to tasks when you feel fully invested in the outcome, and it's this sense of ownership that gives you the confidence to do your best work.

personality_type.name: Openness
personality_type.description: Solving Problems (Openness) concerns how someone thinks about work problems, projects and challenges, how receptive they are to new or different information or approaches, and the way this influences their decision-making.

details.title: first_person_description
details.body: You appear to take a balanced approach to solving problems. You are likely to be able to think of new and original ways of approaching situations, but not at the expense of ignoring well-established solutions, already known to work. This will often involve investigating problems by taking an open-ended view of what might work, and not being afraid to change things if necessary. Most likely, you will have an eye on whether something will be effective both now and in the future. The emphasis will probably be on juggling the facts and making changes, large or small, in order to make a decision that will stand the test of time.

personality_type.name: Emotional Stability
personality_type.description: Managing pressure (Emotional Stability) concerns the manner in which someone deals with pressure and the way in which they control their emotions and underlying tension, in order to stay on task and cope with everyday challenges.

details.title: first_person_description
details.body: You look as if you respond to pressure in a relaxed way but also know when to take things seriously. You seem to be able to let minor irritations go. Your results indicate that you are someone who is generally calm, and not the sort to dwell on things, but who is also 'on guard' at times. You listen to other people and take note of what they say, but are not prone to let criticism interfere with what you do. When it comes to managing your feelings, you tend to respond to situations in a measured manner, as you have a good understanding of your ability to cope. Indeed your friends and colleagues might well describe you as an even-tempered and positive person. By and large you probably feel well able to deal with most of what life hands you.

personality_type.description: Solving Problems (Openness) concerns how someone thinks about work problems, projects and challenges, how receptive they are to new or different information or approaches, and the way this influences their decision-making.

details.title: Leading Others - Success Skills - Emotional Stability
details.body: Is your organization not taking the time to listen to customers? Think of how a “culture of listening” could be integrated into the customer experience.

details.title: Leading Others - Success Skills - Agreeableness
details.body: Moving on after a coworker makes a mistake frees up energy to meet future goals. Focus on the opportunity to learn from the experience so as to avoid making the same mistake.

details.title: Leading Others - Success Skills - Extraversion
details.body: You’re comfortable staying out of the spotlight. Discuss a high-impact decision with your team and present the end result as a group effort.

details.title: Leading Others - Success Skills - Conscientiousness
details.body: Seek out a helping hand. Check in with your coworkers for the purpose of ensuring that deadlines are on track, expectations are met, and nothing is being overlooked.

details.title: Leading Others - Success Skills - Openness
details.body: Your team appreciates when you share what you know. Build a routine to provide everyone with updates, and prepare to include occasional reminders of the team’s higher level vision.

details.title: Candidate Description
details.body: You are up for trying novel tasks and considering new ideas. Steady and content with focusing attention on multiple projects at once, you may worry about how you are being perceived by others and want to manage your reputation.

details.title: Communication - Success Skills - Agreeableness
details.body: When it comes to others, focus on one need at a time. What do they need to know? Or do they just need you to listen?

details.title: Communication - Success Skills - Conscientiousness
details.body: Remember to communicate what you’ve accomplished to others.

details.title: Communication - Success Skills - Emotional Stability
details.body: Talk solutions, not just problems. Focus on both.

details.title: Communication - Success Skills - Extraversion
details.body: Your slower pace can bring calm to a jittery audience.

details.title: Communication - Success Skills - Openness
details.body: Tried-and-true methods are your go-to. Speak clearly. Look people in the eye. Listen.

details.title: Complement
details.body: You are sensitive, even-tempered, compassionate and compatible with many people. Since you are agreeable and enjoy multitasking and doing tasks on the fly in a relaxed, spontaneous way, you often work in a nonlinear fashion, accomplishing a little of this and a little of that.  Finally, you find that those with open-minds are just too flexible and those with too intense a work ethic are too inflexible for you.

details.title: Conflict
details.body: As a lover of people, you are fortunate that you work well with most sorts of people. Often sought out for your amicability, you may find that others may try to dominate and manipulate you, and you may have to adopt a certain amount of assertiveness to be respected. However, you may find that, because of your sensitivity and flexibility, you may be viewed as too laid back and engaging in the process of doing by some, who feel that you get lost in the weeds and are not task oriented enough. Also, others may worry about your emotional vulnerabilities at times.

details.title: Dealing With Stress - Success Skills - Agreeableness
details.body: What worked before? Tell coworkers about a challenge you experienced in the past, and how you worked through it.

details.title: Dealing With Stress - Success Skills - Conscientiousness
details.body: Don’t rush. Take your time to get work done right.

details.title: Dealing With Stress - Success Skills - Emotional Stability
details.body: Take the “chunking” approach. Focus on the next 20 minutes and what you’ll work on then, rather than months at a time.

details.title: Dealing With Stress - Success Skills - Extraversion
details.body: Familiar scents can bring back fond memories. Think about happy times and the smells that went along with them.

details.title: Dealing With Stress - Success Skills - Openness
details.body: Seek comfort in the familiar: wear your comfiest shirt or change your phone’s home screen photo to an old favorite.

details.title: Everyday Adjustments - Success Skills - Agreeableness
details.body: Post on social media about a favorite charity or organization in need to help them fundraise.

details.title: Everyday Adjustments - Success Skills - Conscientiousness
details.body: Is a project unfinished around your home? Think about any “loose ends” you could wrap up.

details.title: Everyday Adjustments - Success Skills - Emotional Stability
details.body: Take a screen break. Spend an afternoon away from your phone, tablet, or laptop. Read a book or magazine, take a long walk, organize a cluttered cabinet.

details.title: Everyday Adjustments - Success Skills - Extraversion
details.body: Try a focused breathing session. Move to a new, quieter spot in your home and take three cleansing breaths.

details.title: Everyday Adjustments - Success Skills - Openness
details.body: Create a routine for your “body clock.” Set your alarm clock for the same time every weekday morning.

details.title: Habits To Build - Success Skills - Agreeableness
details.body: You’re a natural advocate for others. Help out a neglected customer or fatigued coworker.

details.title: Habits To Build - Success Skills - Conscientiousness
details.body: Reflect on what “success” looks like to you. How can you measure your performance?

details.title: Habits To Build - Success Skills - Emotional Stability
details.body: Being prepared makes you feel better. Help the company put plans in place for various outcomes, including emergency response.

details.title: Habits To Build - Success Skills - Extraversion
details.body: “Behind the scenes” is where you like to be. Apply your talents as a team player.

details.title: Habits To Build - Success Skills - Openness
details.body: You’ve got stamina for the “small stuff.” Take on tasks that require persistence.

details.title: Hiring Manager Description
details.body: Cohorts are up for trying novel tasks and considering new ideas. Steady and content with focusing attention on multiple projects at once, this candidate may worry about how they are being perceived by others and want to manage their reputation.

details.title: Teamwork - Success Skills - Agreeableness
details.body: Are you wasting time waiting on a go-ahead from others at every step? Think about what progress you can make on your own.

details.title: Teamwork - Success Skills - Conscientiousness
details.body: Double-check each other. Ask a coworker to remind you to complete key action items, and do the same for them.

details.title: Teamwork - Success Skills - Emotional Stability
details.body: There’s strength in numbers! Think of your workplace team as a “home base” that supports you through the ups and downs of a work week.

details.title: Teamwork - Success Skills - Extraversion
details.body: Stay engaged! Be in touch with your team to say hello from time to time.

details.title: Teamwork - Success Skills - Openness
details.body: Seek out the insights of senior members of the company. What has worked well in the past?

details.title: Working From Home - Success Skills - Agreeableness

details.title: Working From Home - Success Skills - Conscientiousness
details.body: Set incremental goals to motivate yourself.

details.title: Working From Home - Success Skills - Emotional Stability
details.body: Stay informed, but limit the number of updates you seek during the workday.

details.title: Working From Home - Success Skills - Extraversion
details.body: Change your body’s position from time to time. Work while standing to keep your energy up.

details.title: Working From Home - Success Skills - Openness
details.body: Create a home workspace as similar to familiar office spaces as possible.

personalityTypes.name: Openness
personalityTypes.description: Solving Problems (Openness) concerns how someone thinks about work problems, projects and challenges, how receptive they are to new or different information or approaches, and the way this influences their decision-making.

personalityTypes.name: Emotional Stability
personalityTypes.description: Managing pressure (Emotional Stability) concerns the manner in which someone deals with pressure and the way in which they control their emotions and underlying tension, in order to stay on task and cope with everyday challenges.

personalityTypes.name: Conscientiousness
personalityTypes.description: Delivering Results (Conscientiousness) concerns work style and how someone directs their efforts and attention toward completing tasks. The level of discipline, dedication, perseverance, organization and reliability are hallmark factors of this dimension.

personalityTypes.name: Extraversion
personalityTypes.description: Engaging with people (Extraversion) concerns someone’s interest, investment and comfort in developing relationships with others - customers, clients, work groups or colleagues.

personalityTypes.name: Agreeableness
personalityTypes.description: Influencing people (Agreeableness) concerns the way someone balances their emotional understanding of other people, and their respect for differing viewpoints, with the style in which they try to influence or negotiate with them.
